<TEXT>
1-464 FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY 
<F P=103> 94S90010A </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow TAKTIKA (ROTA, BATALON) CHAST VTORAYA </F>
<F P=105>  Russian </F>
CSO 

<F P=106> [Book "Tactics (Company, Battalion), Part II", by Colonel A. </F>
V. Bykov et al, edited by Colonel General Ye. I. Krylov, 
approved by CinC Ground Troops as a textbook for cadets of 
higher combined arms and tank command schools, USSR Ministry of 
Defense, Voyenizdat, 495 pages; indented material with a line 
down the left-hand side is noted in text with "begin" or "end 
side line"] 
  [Text] 
<H5>  Chapter I - Soviet Military Doctrine </H5>
  The Soviet Union firmly and steadfastly follows a Leninist 
peaceloving foreign policy whose chief goal is to create 
favorable external conditions for further development of Soviet 
society and its revolutionary renewal based on perestroyka, to 
ensure that the Soviet people have an opportunity to work under 
conditions of peace and freedom, to eliminate the arms race and 
threat of a new world war, and to strengthen international 
security. Soviet military doctrine serves this goal. 
  It was the Great October Revolution that laid down 
foundations of contemporary USSR military doctrine, and the main 
credit for this goes to V. I. Lenin. He worked out political 
aspects of the doctrine, and the most important provisions of 
military-technical questions of Soviet military doctrine are 
his. He spelled out the purpose and missions of the Armed Forces 
and principles of their organizational development, training and 
employment, and formulated the fundamentals of the socialist 
state's military art. 
  It was in our state that a peace policy and the defense of 
freedom and equal rights of all peoples were proclaimed from the 
first days of its existence, as set forth in the very first 
state acts of Soviet authority adopted in October 1917. Armed 
defense of the October achievements and assurance of peaceful 
conditions for building socialism in our country became one of 
the especially important tasks in this period under conditions 
of fierce attacks by world imperialism and internal 
counterrevolution. 
  In the work "Yedinaya voyennaya doktrina `Krasnaya armiya'" 
["Red Army" Unified Military Doctrine], M. V. Frunze formulated 
the essence of military doctrine for the first time in 1921, 
singling out two fundamental components of its structure, 
technical and political, and directing attention to the fact 
that military doctrine must determine the nature of Armed Forces 
organizational development, troop combat training methods, and 
their "leadership" with consideration of assigned 
missions.[.sup]1[/] 
  Military organizational development of that period had a 
defensive direction, inasmuch as capitalist countries were 
threatening the country with aggression. 
  The Soviet state did everything necessary to prevent war and 
exclude it from the arsenal of means for resolving 
contradictions among states. The struggle to prevent war has 
been an inalienable and very important element of the political 
aspect of Soviet military doctrine since times of the October 
Socialist Revolution. 
  The Great Patriotic War and postwar period confirmed the 
correctness of provisions of Soviet military doctrine and its 
conformity to our socialist state's foreign policy line and to 
requirements for the country's development. At the same time, 
significant changes in the world situation, especially the 
increased aggressiveness of reactionary circles of the largest 
capitalist states, insistently demanded a clear emphasis on the 
defensive nature of Soviet military doctrine and clarification 
of the attitude toward war, above all nuclear war. 
  The contemporary stage of our state's development is 
characterized by revolutionary transformations in all areas of 
society's life and new political thinking in international 
relations. The Soviet Union and allied states base their foreign 
and military policy on the Leninist theory of peaceful 
coexistence and a policy of peace. 
  The USSR's peaceable, open policy finds support in broad 
circles of the world community, which led to important positive 
processes in international relations. It has been acknowledged 
that considering war to be a means of achieving political goals 
is amoral and criminal under present conditions. Today the 
majority of world countries reject the principle of force in 
resolving international problems. At the same time, the enormous 
military potential of the sides, especially the accumulation of 
a large quantity of nuclear weapons and the sharply increased 
casualty-producing properties of conventional weapons, made the 
problem of preventing a new world war extraordinarily acute. 
Under these conditions the Soviet Union advanced the concept of 
equal security for all based on a balance of interests and on 
exclusion of violence from the practice of relations among 
states. In accordance with this, the Soviet state's Armed Forces 
are given as the priority mission that of repelling an 
aggressor's invasion by defensive operations. 
  In connection with the new approach to problems of war and 
peace, Soviet military doctrine presently represents a set of 
officially adopted, fundamental views on prevention of war, 
military organizational development, preparation of the country 
and USSR Armed Forces for repelling aggression, and methods of 
fighting a war in defense of socialism. Stemming objectively 
from the nature of the Soviet social and state system, this 
doctrine has an unequivocally defensive direction and is 
subordinated to the primary mission of preventing war, both 
nuclear as well as conventional, and protecting the country from 
possible outside aggression. 
  The main goal of our military doctrine is to prevent war, 
strengthen international security and protect the homeland, 
inasmuch as herein lies the principal meaning of our foreign 
policy and a very important condition for the country's 
successful development. 
  Soviet military doctrine conforms to the goals of military 
operations in repelling aggression and at the same time it takes 
into account general USSR defense missions. In case of 
aggression the Soviet people and their Armed Forces will defend 
their Motherland with all determination. 
  Soviet military doctrine includes two aspects--political and 
military- technical. 
  The political aspect is the principal one, since 
it reflects Soviet state policy in the defense area and 
determines the attitude toward problems of war--its prevention, 
the nature of military threat to the USSR and its allies, and 
political tasks stemming from this. 
  The main direction of the political aspect of Soviet 
military 
doctrine consists of the following provisions: resolution of 
international issues only in a peaceful way; total exclusion of 
world war, both nuclear as well as conventional; and that the 
security of peoples can be only mutual and, within the framework 
of the international community, universal. 
  In accordance with these provisions the Soviet Union 
never will begin military operations first if it does 
not become the target of armed aggression itself. The Soviet 
Union never will employ nuclear weapons first. 
  While coming out in favor of mutual rejection of the use of 
military force, the Soviet Union at the same time is taking 
necessary steps to strengthen its defense capability. 
  The principal military-political tasks of the Soviet state 
stem from the political aspect of doctrine: a) in peacetime to 
keep the country's defense capability at the level of necessary 
defense sufficiency, not allow initiation of a world war by 
imperialism, and ensure constant readiness of the Armed Forces 
to repel armed aggression; b) in case of war to repel 
aggression, defend the Motherland, fulfill allied obligations, 
inflict decisive damage on the aggressor and deprive him of the 
capability to continue the war. 
  The military-technical aspect of Soviet military 
doctrine is subordinated to the political aspect. It determines 
the following provisions: nature of the military threat and 
warfare; the Armed Forces makeup and structure necessary for 
repelling aggression and defending the country; methods of 
employing the Armed Forces in case of war; and the direction of 
Armed Forces training to perform defense missions. 
  The following missions are the basis of this aspect of 
military doctrine: ensure military-strategic parity and not 
allow military superiority of armies of the probable enemy; 
maintain sufficient defense might; prepare retaliatory 
operations to repel aggression and give a crushing rebuff to the 
aggressor as the principal method of Armed Forces operations. 
  Considering the development of all kinds of weapons, 
including nuclear weapons, in armies of NATO countries, the USSR 
Armed Forces must be trained to repel aggression to an equal 
extent with or without the use of nuclear weapons. In case of 
nuclear war, the USSR Armed Forces must be capable of inflicting 
unacceptable damage on the aggressor. 
  Our state, which adheres to a defensive military doctrine, 
has no aggressive intentions with respect to other states and is 
not preparing to initiate military operations against them. It 
will begin retaliatory operations only in case it is subjected 
to armed attack itself. It carries out Armed Forces 
organizational development based on the concept of military 
sufficiency. 
  Defense sufficiency is understood to mean the level of 
military potentials of opposing sides (states) that ensures each 
of them guaranteed protection and repulse of aggression but is 
insufficient to conduct large scale offensive operations. The 
level of reasonable defense sufficiency is determined in such a 
way as to ensure strategic stability at the lowest possible 
level of the sides' military confrontation, reliable repulse of 
aggression, and successful performance of strategic missions 
while maintaining parity in strategic nuclear assets, equality 
of military forces in principal theaters of military operations, 
and their sufficiency for defense on other axes. 
  The defensive nature of Soviet military doctrine and the 
level of military sufficiency are determined by the fact that 
there are no classes in the USSR interested in war and that 
preemptive wars with a preventive or precautionary goal are 
alien to the nature of socialism. The USSR views attack, 
including nuclear attack or an attack using only conventional 
weapons, as a crime against the people of its country and 
against mankind as a whole. 
  But the Armed Forces must be in high combat and mobilization 
readiness to preclude surprise aggression, and in case of 
aggression they must repel an enemy invasion by an active 
defense and then rout him by counteroffensive operations. The 
immediate delivery of surprise retaliatory counterstrikes 
against the enemy is envisaged with the beginning of his 
aggression. Defense will be their basis at the beginning of a 
war. 
Footnotes 
  1. See M. V. Frunze, "Izbrannyye proizvedeniya" [Selected 
Works], Moscow, Voyenizdat, 1984, pp 34-35. 
<H5>  Chapter II - Principles of Employing the Company and </H5>
Battalion in Battle 
<H5>  1. Combat Employment of the Motorized Rifle (Tank) Company </H5>
and Battalion 
  Modern combined arms battle is conducted through united 
efforts of all troops involved (Diagram 1), but the principal 
role in winning victory in combined arms battle rests with 
motorized rifle and tank subunits. Only they are capable of 
completing the enemy's rout and seizing his territory. They 
fight the battle, and subunits of other combat arms work 
together with them to perform these missions. 
  Organizationally the motorized rifle company [MRC] (tank 
company [TC]) is part of a motorized rifle battalion [MRB] (tank 
battalion [TB]). It is a tactical subunit and serves as a unit 
of calculation for various tactical calculations performed in 
the motorized rifle regiment [MRR] (tank regiment [TR]). 
  Organizationally the MRB (TB) is part of an MRR (TR). It is 
the basic combined arms tactical subunit and the tactical unit 
of calculation of the formation in planning battle and 
performing calculations for making a march and for transport 
movement by rail, water routes, air and so on. 
  The MRC (TC) and MRB (TB), outfitted with modern arms and 
with combat and other vehicles, have powerful fire, high 
mobility, maneuverability, armor protection, and the capability 
to resist effects of enemy mass destruction weapons. 
  A company (battalion) can march great distances and quickly 
exploit results of nuclear strikes to complete the enemy's rout. 
In coordination with adjacent subunits or independently, it is 
capable of successfully attacking or firmly holding an occupied 
strongpoint (area) in the defense on various terrain and in any 
weather, and of destroying enemy airborne assault forces, 
helicopters and other low-flying targets. 
  In the defense the MRC (TC) and MRB (TB) are capable of 
inflicting damage on the enemy by organized fire of all weapons 
on approaches to the FEBA; repelling his tank and infantry 
assaults and helicopter strikes; stubbornly holding an occupied 
strongpoint (defense area); and, when the enemy has penetrated 
the defense, completing his rout by a counterattack by the 
second echelon. 
  Coordinating among themselves as well as with artillery and 
subunits of other combat arms and special troops, the MRC (TC) 
and MRB (TB) perform the primary mission of immediate 
destruction of enemy personnel and weapons in close combat. By 
exploiting results of nuclear and fire damage of the enemy and 
skillfully combining fire and movement in the attack, they can 
assault the enemy swiftly and destroy his personnel, tanks, 
infantry fighting vehicles [IFV's], artillery and antitank [AT] 
weapons as well as means of nuclear and chemical attack, 
aircraft and helicopters. 
  They are capable of taking enemy defensive positions from 
the 
move, repelling counterattacks, and developing the attack in the 
depth at a rapid pace. They can conduct a meeting battle, force 
water obstacles from the move, negotiate obstacles and 
destructive damage, pursue a retreating enemy at a fast pace and 
capture intermediate defensive lines in the depth of a defense 
from the move. 
  As a rule, a company (battalion) fights as part of the MRB 
or 
TB (MRR or TR) or independently, and may operate in a 
reconnaissance detachment, in a forward security element or 
flank security element (advance guard, rear guard), in a 
tactical airborne assault force (raiding detachment) or an 
enveloping detachment; it may defend a forward position 
(positions in the security zone); and it also may fight a 
defensive battle in the mountains, the desert, and northern 
areas. 
  The battalion mortar battery and grenade launcher platoon 
[GLP] usually remain subordinate to the battalion commander and 
as a rule are used at full strength to support first echelon 
MRC's. Sometimes the GLP may be attached at full strength to an 
MRC defending on an axis of concentration of battalion main 
efforts or it may be attached by squads to first echelon 
companies. 
  The battalion antitank platoon [ATP] usually remains 
subordinate to the battalion commander and as a rule is used at 
full strength on a likely avenue of tank approach to repel 
assaults by enemy tanks and other armored vehicles. The platoon 
may be attached to first echelon companies at full strength or 
by squads on terrain providing concealment and rough terrain. 
  The attached air defense subunit as a rule remains directly 
subordinate to the battalion commander. 
  Company (battalion) reinforcement. For greater 
independence in fighting, subunits of other combat arms and 
special troops usually are attached to or assigned in support of 
a company (battalion). 
  Attached reinforcing subunits become fully subordinate to 
the 
company (battalion) commander. He assigns them missions in the 
course of battle, but if necessary they may be used to perform 
missions under the plan of the senior commander (chief). For 
example, in penetration of an enemy defense an artillery 
battalion attached to a maneuver battalion will take part in 
artillery preparation of the assault and engage the enemy under 
the senior commander's plan. 
  Supporting subunits remain subordinate to the senior 
commander (chief) and perform missions he assigns as well as 
missions assigned by the commander of the company (battalion) 
which they are supporting, within limits of allocated force 
assets (detail). 
  The number and makeup of subunits to be attached depend on 
the nature of the mission to be performed by subunits and on 
situation conditions. 
  A mortar or artillery battery and an AT, grenade launcher, 
combat engineer, and flamethrower subunit may be attached to an 
MRC and also a tank platoon [TP] in the defense and when 
attacking in the city, in the mountains and in the forest. 
  An artillery battery, motorized rifle subunit and combat 
engineer subunit may be attached to a TC. 
  An MRB (TB) may receive as reinforcement one or two TC's 
(MRC's), an artillery battalion or battery, a subunit of AT 
weapons, an air defense subunit, and also subunits of engineer 
and chemical troops. 
  Artillery subunits are intended for engaging enemy means of 
nuclear and chemical attack, precision weapon systems, 
artillery, tanks, IFV's, AT and other weapons, and also enemy 
personnel, helicopters at landing sites, air defense weapons, 
command and control [C[.sup]2[/]] facilities and electronic 
equipment. In addition, they demolish enemy fortifications and 
may carry out remote mining of terrain, provide illumination 
support in conducting a night battle, lay aerosol (smoke) 
screens and perform other missions in the course of battle. 
Artillery subunits perform fire missions from indirect firing 
positions, selecting them at a distance of 2-6 km from the 
friendly FEBA. In a number of cases (when fighting in a city, 
repelling counterattacks, penetrating a fortified area) 
individual pieces, platoons and batteries may be used to conduct 
direct fire to destroy enemy tanks, other armored targets and AT 
weapons. 
  Subunits of antitank guided missile [ATGM] systems and of AT 
grenade launchers are intended for repelling assaults by enemy 
tanks and other armored vehicles. In addition, they can be used 
to destroy weapons situated not only in open, but also in 
covered fortification structures, and in certain cases also 
enemy combat helicopters flying at low altitudes. 
  A grenade launcher subunit is a powerful fire delivery means 
of the MRB. It is intended for engaging enemy personnel and 
weapons in the open, in emplacements (trenches) and behind 
terrain folds. Grenade launchers are especially effective in 
repelling enemy mechanized infantry assaults ahead of the FEBA 
and repelling their counterattacks in the course of an attack. 
  The air defense subunit is intended for destroying the 
airborne enemy at extremely low and low altitudes. Being in the 
battalion battle, approach march, or march formation, it 
conducts fire against airborne targets in movement or from short 
halts, from afloat in forcing water obstacles, and from prepared 
firing positions on defense and when disposed at the halt. In 
addition, the air defense subunit may be used to combat enemy 
ground targets and targets on the water's surface. 
  Engineer subunits are attached to perform engineer 
reconnaissance of the enemy, terrain and installations; fortify 
strongpoints, positions and disposition areas; conduct engineer 
measures of maskirovka [lit. "camouflage", however, includes 
"concealment" and "deception" -- FBIS] and protection against 
precision weapons; emplace engineer obstacles; breach obstacles 
and rubble; clear mines from terrain and installations; prepare 
and maintain crossings during a forcing of water obstacles; 
perform measures of preparing and maintaining water supply 
points, and so on. 
  Subunits of chemical troops are intended for conducting 
radiological and chemical reconnaissance, radiological and 
chemical monitoring, decontamination of subunits, and maskirovka 
of subunits with aerosols (smoke), and for inflicting losses on 
the enemy with incendiary munitions. 
  Flamethrower subunits attached to the battalion are intended 
for engaging enemy personnel, weapons, and combat and other 
vehicles and creating centers of fire. The battalion commander 
usually attaches them to first echelon MRC's. As a rule, they 
operate in those companies' battle formations, firing 
flamethrowers on the move, from short halts or from in place. 
  The battalion signal subunit is intended for establishing 
and 
maintaining stable communications with subordinate (attached) 
subunits, supporting C[.sup]2[/], and maintaining 
communications with the senior commander (chief) and adjacent 
subunits. 
  Battalion support subunits are intended for servicing, 
maintenance and minor repairs of weapons and vehicles, 
maintaining reserves of ammunition, fuel and other supplies, 
delivering them to subunits, replenishing ammunition and fuel, 
and providing hot meals for the personnel. 
  The battalion aid station is intended for searching for the 
wounded, transporting or carrying them from the battlefield, 
giving paramedic assistance to the wounded and sick, and 
preparing them for evacuation. 
  Company (battalion) formations. An MRC (TC) or MRB 
(TB) may operate in march, approach march or battle formation 
depending on specific situation conditions. 
  The company (battalion) march formation is the 
alignment of subunits for column movement. It is used in making 
a march and executing a covert maneuver and should ensure a high 
rate of movement and rapid deployment into approach march and 
battle formation. The march formation also should ensure least 
vulnerability of personnel, weapons, and combat and other 
vehicles to enemy mass destruction weapons and air and precision 
weapon strikes, and maintenance of stable C[.sup]2[/] of 
subunits. 
  The company (battalion) march formation usually consists of 
the main body column and security. Depending on specific 
situation conditions and presence of means of reinforcement, the 
company (battalion) main body column may have a varying 
alignment. When a battalion moves along an independent route, a 
forward security element consisting of a reinforced platoon or 
reinforced company is sent forward as security from the main 
body column to a distance of from 5 to 10 km, and patrol squads 
or tanks are sent to flanks and the rear. 
  The company (battalion) approach march formation 
is the alignment of company (battalion) subunits for movement in 
columns dispersed laterally and in depth. The company 
(battalion) approach march formation is formed by platoon 
(company) columns, and that of an MRC (MRB) operating in 
dismounted formation without BMP's (BTR's) also by squad 
columns. The position of platoons (companies) in the company 
(battalion) approach march formation may be in a line, wedge, 
reverse wedge, echelon right, or echelon left. 
  The approach march formation is used to ensure swift 
deployment of subunits into battle formation; least 
vulnerability of subunits to mass destruction weapons, air 
strikes, precision weapon strikes and artillery fire; attainment 
of high rates of advance; and rapid negotiation of various 
obstacles and areas of contamination, destructive damage, fires 
and floods. 
  The battalion commander determines companies' places in the 
approach march formation with consideration of the planned 
battalion battle formation. Places of platoons (squads) in the 
company (platoon) approach march formation are indicated only if 
necessary. They operate primarily in a fixed alignment of 
platoons (squads): the first in the center, second on the right 
flank, third on the left flank. 
  Intervals and distances are 150-300 m between platoon 
columns 
and 300-600 m between company columns. A company intended for 
operations in the second echelon or reserve proceeds at a 
distance of 1.5-2 km. 
  TC's (TP's) attached to an MRB as a rule proceed in front of 
the MRC's (MRP's). Motorized rifle subunits attached to a TB 
usually proceed behind the TC's (TP's). 
  Weapons which have been left directly subordinate to the 
company (battalion) commander proceed in places in the approach 
march formation indicated by the commander. 
  A company (battalion) deploys from march into approach march 
formation successively into platoon (company) columns and squad 
columns independently when they reach indicated deployment lines 
(points) or at a command (signal) from the company (battalion) 
commander. 
  The company (battalion) battle formation is the 
alignment of subunits for fighting. It should correspond to the 
mission received and the commander's concept and ensure 
successful conduct of battle with use both of nuclear as well as 
only conventional weapons; greatest involvement of weapons in 
battle and full use of subunit combat capabilities; swift 
exploitation of results of nuclear and fire damage of the enemy 
and favorable terrain conditions; timely buildup of efforts in 
the course of battle and timely execution of a maneuver. In 
addition, it should ensure stability and activeness of subunits 
in the defense; least vulnerability of subunits to strikes by 
all kinds of weapons, including precision weapons; maintenance 
of continuous coordination; and convenience of C[.sup]2[/]. 
  The company battle formation consists of first echelon 
subunits (and in the defense also second echelon subunits), 
company weapons and reinforcing subunits; it may include an 
armored group and fire ambushes. 
  The battalion battle formation consists of first echelon 
subunits; second echelon or reserve subunits; and weapons which 
remain directly subordinate to the battalion commander. 
  The battalion battle formation in the defense also may 
include an armored group and fire ambushes. 
  The battalion first echelon usually includes MRC's (TC's) 
with means of reinforcement. When the MRB battle formation is 
aligned in two echelons, the first echelon as a rule includes 
two MRC's and tank subunits attached to the battalion. An MRC 
usually is assigned to the second echelon. When the battle 
formation is aligned in one echelon, from a platoon to an MRC 
may be assigned to the reserve. 
  An attached artillery battalion or battery, air defense 
subunit, and ATP usually may be in the mix of weapons remaining 
at the battalion commander's disposal. 
<H5>  2. Methodology for Calculating Company and Battalion Combat </H5>
Capabilities in Battle 
  The MRC (TC) and MRB (TB) have rather powerful weapons and 
combat vehicles in the inventory, but war experience showed it 
has to be used skillfully and most effectively in battle, i.e., 
take fullest advantage of combat capabilities. Therefore the 
company (battalion) commander's thorough knowledge of combat 
capabilities of weapons which his subunit has, counting attached 
and supporting troops, and also of the personnel's morale and 
political attitude is an important condition for making a 
substantiated decision and permits exercising competent 
C[.sup]2[/] of subordinate troops in battle. 
  Frunze said that the commander's art is manifested in the 
ability to select from the diversity of means at his disposal 
those which will provide best results in a given situation and 
at a given time. 
  In organizing for battle, a large number of questions arise 
for the company (battalion) commander which he is obligated to 
resolve before the beginning of battle: How many and what forces 
will have to be put to use to perform the combat mission he has 
received? What result of battle should be expected with a given 
makeup of friendly and enemy forces and assets considering 
conditions of the terrain and meteorological situation, state of 
weather, time of year and day and so on? 
  He can obtain correct answers to the questions posed above 
if 
he knows and is able to assess the combat capabilities not only 
of friendly but also of enemy troops. 
  Just what should we understand combat capabilities to mean? 
  Combat capabilities in general terms customarily 
are understood to be quantitative and qualitative indicators 
characterizing subunit capabilities to perform specific combat 
missions in a prescribed time and in a specific situation. 
Combat capabilities depend on the number of personnel, the 
subunit (unit) in question, level of its preparedness for 
fighting, and availability and status of weapons and of combat 
and other vehicles; ability of command personnel to exercise 
C[.sup]2[/] of subunits; and troop organizational structure 
and state of supply. They also depend on the enemy makeup and 
nature of opposition; terrain conditions; and meteorological 
situation (state of weather, time of year and day) in which the 
battle is being organized and fought. 
  Company (battalion) combat capabilities also depend on the 
kind and nature of upcoming battle. 
  Combat capabilities of subunits of different combat arms are 
expressed by specific indicators. For example, combat 
capabilities of the MRC (TC) or MRB (TB) are described in terms 
of the makeup of enemy forces and assets which they are capable 
of routing (destroying) in an attack (repelling an enemy attack 
in the defense); width of attack frontage (size of a defense 
area [or] strongpoint); depth of subunits' combat missions and 
their rate of advance; depth of fire effect against enemy 
targets; radius of actions of weapons and time for preparing 
them to deliver a strike, and so on. Fire capabilities for 
destroying enemy tanks, IFV's, aircraft and other weapons may be 
determined separately. 
  Company (battalion) combat capabilities can be examined in 
terms of kinds and means of destruction (tanks, BMP's, BTR's, 
artillery, small arms). In addition, the capability of creating 
necessary densities of forces and assets per kilometer of 
frontage is taken into account. 
  It is common knowledge that firepower, striking power and 
maneuverability are the components of company (battalion) combat 
capabilities. 
  The firepower of an MRC (TC) and MRB (TB) as a 
rule is formed from fire capabilities of organic and attached 
artillery, tanks, BMP's, AT weapons, air defense weapons and all 
kinds of small arms. Minefields also are included in firepower 
in conducting defensive battle. 
  The firepower of an MRC (TC) and MRB (TB) usually is 
expressed by the total scope of fire missions which can be 
performed by organic and attached reinforcing weapons with the 
amount of ammunition allocated in accordance with existing 
norms. Damage inflicted on the enemy and expressed by a certain 
degree of his neutralization or destruction is the result of 
realization of firepower. 
  The number of objectives (targets) to be engaged and extent 
of their damage (including platoon strongpoints) usually are 
included in the indicators of MRC (MRB) firepower. The number of 
enemy weapons and combat vehicles (especially tanks and ATGM's) 
destroyed and the mathematical expectation of damage inflicted 
on a grouping of enemy troops is determined without fail. 
  The striking power of an MRC or TC (MRB or TB) is 
manifested in the capability of these subunits to deliver 
powerful strikes against the enemy by a combination of fire and 
movement in an indicated direction. Organic, attached and 
supporting artillery, tanks, BMP's, BTR's, AT weapons, automatic 
grenade launchers and all kinds of small arms may take part in 
the company (battalion) in carrying out a strike. Fire is 
conducted on the move and from short halts. Taking advantage of 
the fire of senior chiefs and conducting fire from all kinds of 
their own weapons, company (battalion) subunits swiftly advance 
into the depth, destroying surviving enemy weapons and personnel 
in the course of movement and take indicated lines (areas) of 
the terrain or strongpoints in the enemy defense. 
  Striking power is characterized above all by densities of 
forces and assets established on the entire attack frontage and 
on the axis of concentration of main efforts and by the number 
of motorized rifle and tank platoons (companies), tanks, BMP's, 
BTR's, guns, mortars, and AT and other weapons per kilometer of 
attack frontage. Striking power in the defense is realized in 
routing an enemy who has penetrated the defense, i.e., in 
conducting counterattacks and completing the rout of an enemy 
who has penetrated. 
  The striking power of an attacking company (battalion) 
depends on the density of forces and assets of a defending or 
attacking enemy and is characterized by the ratio of opposing 
sides' forces and assets. 
  Obviously, the higher the densities of forces and assets 
established by a company (battalion) in battle and the less they 
are for the enemy, the greater will be the force of the 
company's (battalion's) attack and consequently it will perform 
the assigned mission faster. 
  As a rule, armored vehicles (tanks, BMP's, BTR's) with their 
weapons and personnel, which usually fight together, make up the 
basis of company (battalion) striking power. They are capable of 
destroying enemy weapons not only by fire, but also by tracks 
(wheels). Striking power and firepower are manifested in 
inseparable unity here, which is achieved by organizing and 
maintaining precise, continuous coordination of all forces and 
assets participating in the battle. 
  Maneuverability is a property of force elements of 
different branches of the Armed Forces, combat arms and special 
troops describing their degree of mobility and capability for 
quickly accomplishing movement and deployment in preparation for 
and in the course of combat operations, and the capability of 
military vehicles to change speed and direction of movement 
quickly. 
  Maneuverability of a company (battalion) is its capability 
to 
redeploy and change the mutual position of forces and assets in 
an organized, rapid manner; assume a particular alignment; make 
ready for particular operations at a certain time; build up the 
force of the initial attack; transfer efforts from one axis to 
another; cross zones of radioactive and chemical contamination 
and areas of destructive damage, roadblocks and fires; and 
retarget one's weapons for simultaneous engagement of the most 
important enemy targets. In addition, maneuverability in a 
defense describes the capability of subunits to occupy a defense 
in an organized, rapid manner and move battle formation elements 
to any threatened axis in short time periods for taking up a 
defense, conducting counterattacks, destroying a landed enemy 
airborne assault force and so on. 
  Preempting the enemy in opening fire and in delivering an 
attack is the result of realizing maneuverability, which 
contributes to fuller use of firepower, striking power and a 
favorable position. Preempting the enemy in seizing lines 
favorable for defense and building up efforts on threatened axes 
are the result of realization of maneuver capabilities of 
subunits in the defense. Maneuverability of the company 
(battalion) in the attack usually is described in terms of time 
indicators for execution of a maneuver by subunits. 
  Methodology of calculating company (battalion) 
firepower. Company (battalion) firepower is made up of the 
offensive potential of organic and attached subunits of 
artillery, AT and air defense weapons, BMP's, tanks, as well as 
small arms. Therefore the methodology of firepower calculations 
consists of a number of independent, individual methodologies 
for the kinds of weapons. 
  Methodology of calculating damage of the enemy by 
artillery fire. Combat capabilities of artillery are 
described in terms of fire and maneuver capabilities and range 
of fire. Fire capabilities are the basic indicator of artillery 
combat capabilities and are expressed by the scope of fire 
missions performed by it simultaneously or successively in 
specific situation conditions. 
  Artillery performs the following missions with its fire in 
battle: engages means of nuclear and chemical attack, precision 
weapon systems and artillery; engages tanks, IFV's, and AT and 
other weapons; engages personnel, helicopters at landing sites, 
air defense weapons, C[.sup]2[/] facilities and electronic 
equipment; demolishes enemy fortifications; performs remote 
mining of terrain and illumination support; and lays aerosol 
(smoke) screens. 
  Artillery subunits can have various artillery systems in the 
inventory. Their characteristics are given in Table 1. 


Table 1 - Principal Specifications and Performance Characteristics of Guns, 
Mortars and Fighting Vehicles 

                            Self- Propelled Guns 

