battalion 


  It is customary to consider that 70 percent of capabilities 
of AT weapons and tanks are used in combating enemy tanks and 30 
percent in combating enemy IFV's, APC's and other armored 
targets. Capabilities of those means to combat enemy APC's and 
IFV's are 2-3 times greater than against tanks, since APC's and 
IFV's have weak armor protection, which protects personnel only 
against bullets and against artillery and mortar round 
fragments, and naturally the APC's and IFV's will be disabled 
after being hit by the very first round. 
  Methodology of calculating company (battalion) 
capabilities for damaging the enemy by small arms fire. 
Mathematical expectation of damage done to enemy personnel is 
the basic indicator of company (battalion) capabilities of 
damaging the enemy by small arms fire. Fire capabilities of 
damaging the enemy by small arms fire usually are calculated 
only in subunits. 
  The calculation methodology is based on a comparison of the 
sides' small arms fire densities expressed by the number of 
bullets per meter of frontage in the indicated sector (zone) of 
fire. Experience has established that when a company attacking 
in dismounted formation comes to within 400 m of the enemy 
defense, it commences fire from all kinds of weapons against his 
forward edge with a density of at least 8-10 bullets per minute 
per meter of frontage and is conducted with that density for 4 
minutes (in an assault at a rate of 100 m in one minute). Such a 
fire density leads to enemy personnel losses of up to 30 percent 
on the forward edge of defense. 
  The procedure for calculating subunit fire capabilities of 
damaging the enemy by small arms fire is as follows: determine 
the number of a battalion's MRC's operating in the first 
echelon; count the number of assault rifles, machineguns and 
other weapons in each company; then, by dividing their 
cumulative effective rate of fire by the company (battalion) 
attack frontage, determine how many bullets will be fired in one 
minute per meter of frontage. 
  Methodology of calculating striking power of 
subunits. The magnitude of subunits' striking power is 
judged from the quantitative makeup, densities, and in the final 
account the number of forces and assets of opposing sides and 
rates of advance. The densities and ratio of close-combat forces 
and assets permit drawing a conclusion about the capability of 
routing the enemy and performing the assigned mission. Densities 
in a company are figured by squads and in a battalion by 
platoons. For example, to conduct a successful attack it is 
necessary to have a superiority of 23 times in favor of 
attacking subunits in the company (battalion) attack frontage, 
to create a superiority of 4-6 times in a penetration sector 
(i.e., overwhelming superiority over the enemy), and thereby, 
taking advantage of the superiority achieved, to assault the 
enemy swiftly right after the fire, rout him and capture the 
designated line from the move. 
  Nine motorized rifle squads [MRS's] and an AT squad carry 
the 
striking power of a BTR-equipped MRC. Usually up to 2-3 platoons 
of tanks operate together with the company on its axis of 
attack, which considerably increases its striking power. In a 
BMP-equipped company the main striking power consists of the 
BMP's (11 of them), which can successfully fight not only enemy 
personnel, but also his tanks and other armored targets. But 
even a BMP-equipped company must coordinate closely with tank 
subunits. 
  Nine MRP's and 33 BMP's are the basis of striking power of a 
BMP-equipped MRB. The experience of field fire exercises which 
have been held showed that a BMP- equipped MRB reinforced by a 
TC and attacking in a 1-2 km frontage is capable of destroying 
all main weapons in 2-3 platoon strongpoints at one line (400 m 
wide and 200 m deep, gaps of 200 m or more between enemy platoon 
strongpoints), expending 0.2-0.3 unit of fire of different 
ammunition for this. 
  A BTR-equipped MRB reinforced by two TC's also has the very 
same capabilities. The TB of an MRR usually is attached to 
MRB's. The striking power of MRC's and MRB's is considerably 
increased because of the tanks. The TB of a TR can 
simultaneously destroy weapons in 2-3 platoon strongpoints, 
i.e., up to a mechanized infantry company, by gun and machinegun 
fire of 30 tanks. Working closely together with the TC attached 
to the battalion, exploiting results of nuclear and fire damage 
of the enemy, and in coordination with adjacent subunits, an MRC 
is capable of completing the rout of an enemy in 2-3 platoon 
points during the time of battalion execution of the mission. 
For their part, an MRB reinforced by tanks and the TB of a TR 
are capable of completing the destruction of personnel and 
weapons in 8-9 platoon strongpoints successively at three lines 
in a day's battle, i.e., routing up to three enemy companies. 
  The magnitude of indicators of striking power of 
counterattacking subunits depends on the number and quality of 
TP's and MRP's being used for the attack which have tanks and 
BMP's (BTR's) in their makeup, and also on the number of AT 
weapons operating together with the counterattacking subunits. 
The higher the density of these forces and assets, the greater 
will be the indicators of striking power. Based on experience of 
the Great Patriotic War and postwar scientific research 
exercises using only conventional weapons, a superiority of 2-3 
times in forces and assets over the enemy in favor of the 
counterattacking subunits was considered sufficient for routing 
an enemy who had penetrated if he had not managed to consolidate 
at the line reached. If an enemy who has penetrated is being 
routed under conditions of the use of nuclear weapons, then 
equal or one and one-half times superiority is sufficient. 
  Based on field fire exercise experience, under conditions of 
the use of nuclear weapons a BMP-equipped MRC working together 
with a TP (TC) can rout a penetrated enemy of up to a mechanized 
infantry company in strength. 
  A BMP-equipped MRB reinforced by one TC and a BTR-equipped 
MRB reinforced by two TC's, with an expenditure of 0.2-0.3 unit 
of fire of different ammunition and delivery of an attack 
against the flank and rear of the penetrated enemy is capable, 
in coordination with adjacent battalions, of routing a 
penetrated grouping equal to its own makeup. 
  The TB of a TR has approximately the very same capabilities 
under the very same conditions. 
  Thus, a rout (or completion of a rout together with the 
regiment's second echelon) of an enemy grouping which has 
penetrated the defense can be the result of realization of the 
striking power of subunits in the defense. 
  The depth of possible advance of counterattacking subunits 
is 
determined by the depth of disposition of enemy forces and 
assets which have penetrated the defense. 
  Methodology for calculating maneuver capabilities. 
Maneuverability of the company and battalion is determined by 
the maneuver qualities of their organic and attached subunits in 
terms of speed, tempo, time, displacement and readiness for 
certain actions. The company (battalion) may employ a maneuver 
of fire, forces and assets. 
  A maneuver of fire is used for more effective 
engagement of the enemy. It consists of a timely concentration 
of the fire of organic and attached subunits against one target 
or a group of important targets, and the transfer of fire from 
one target to another and distribution of fire against several 
targets. The time from transmission of commands to the burst of 
a projectile (munition) at the target is the basic indicator 
characterizing capabilities of the maneuver of fire. It depends 
on the kind of target (objective) (planned or opportunity 
target) against which fire is commenced. The time of delivery of 
a fire strike against an opportunity target is formed from the 
time for transmitting commands and preparing firing data. If 
fire is conducted against a planned target, then time 
expenditures for preparing new firing data are not taken into 
account, since it was done in advance. 
  Maneuver of forces and assets (subunits). A 
maneuver is executed to occupy a more favorable position for 
delivering a strike against the most vulnerable place in the 
enemy combat formation, especially his flank and rear, and to 
move friendly subunits out from under an enemy strike. A 
maneuver of forces and assets can be accomplished along roads or 
cross country routes and by air or water. The maneuver should be 
simple in concept and be executed swiftly, covertly and as a 
surprise to the enemy. Timely, fullest exploitation of results 
of nuclear and fire damage of the enemy should be made the basis 
of a maneuver of forces and assets (subunits). A close 
envelopment, deep envelopment, their combination, and the 
withdrawal are kinds of subunit maneuver. The close envelopment 
is a maneuver executed to move subunits for an attack against an 
enemy flank. The deep envelopment is a deeper maneuver executed 
by subunits to attack the enemy from the rear. A close 
envelopment usually is accomplished in close tactical and fire 
coordination and a deep envelopment only in tactical 
coordination with subunits attacking from the front. A 
withdrawal is a maneuver used to move friendly troops out from 
under an attack by superior enemy forces, to win time and to 
occupy a more favorable line (area). A withdrawal is conducted 
only by permission or order of the senior commander. In the 
defense a maneuver is executed to replace or reinforce subunits 
which have suffered losses, conduct counterattacks, occupy 
alternate positions and lines of firing positions, and destroy 
an enemy who has moved to the flank or rear of a strongpoint 
(defense area). 
  The general content of a maneuver of company (battalion) 
forces and assets on the terrain is made up of the following 
actions: leaving occupied areas of a position or leaving 
occupied lines; closing up subunits into columns and extending 
the columns; shifting to new areas, positions or lines and 
deploying to perform the combat mission. 
  Time of executing a maneuver is the basic indicator of a 
maneuver of forces and assets (Table 4). 


Table 4 - Subunit Maneuver Capabilities 

Subunit Actions                            Time, min 

In the defense 

